types.name: CommittableBranch
types.description:
A git ref for a commit to be appended to.

The ref must be a branch, i.e. its fully qualified name must start
with `refs/heads/` (although the input is not required to be fully
qualified).

The Ref may be specified by its global node ID or by the
`repositoryNameWithOwner` and `branchName`.

### Examples

Specify a branch using a global node ID:

    { "id": "MDM6UmVmMTpyZWZzL2hlYWRzL21haW4=" }

Specify a branch using `repositoryNameWithOwner` and `branchName`:

    {
      "repositoryNameWithOwner": "github/graphql-client",
      "branchName": "main"
    }

fields.name: colors
fields.description: A list of hex color codes used in this calendar. The darker the color, the more contributions it represents.

fields.name: isHalloween
fields.description: Determine if the color set was chosen because it's currently Halloween.

fields.name: months
fields.description: A list of the months of contributions in this calendar.

fields.name: totalContributions
fields.description: The count of total contributions in the calendar.

fields.name: weeks
fields.description: A list of the weeks of contributions in this calendar.

types.name: ContributionCalendarDay
types.description: Represents a single day of contributions on GitHub by a user.

fields.name: color
fields.description: The hex color code that represents how many contributions were made on this day compared to others in the calendar.

fields.name: contributionCount
fields.description: How many contributions were made by the user on this day.

fields.name: contributionLevel
fields.description: Indication of contributions, relative to other days. Can be used to indicate which color to represent this day on a calendar.

fields.name: date
fields.description: The day this square represents.

fields.name: weekday
fields.description: A number representing which day of the week this square represents, e.g., 1 is Monday.

types.name: ContributionCalendarMonth
types.description: A month of contributions in a user's contribution graph.

fields.name: firstDay
fields.description: The date of the first day of this month.

fields.name: name
fields.description: The name of the month.

fields.name: totalWeeks
fields.description: How many weeks started in this month.

fields.name: year
fields.description: The year the month occurred in.

types.name: ContributionCalendarWeek
types.description: A week of contributions in a user's contribution graph.

fields.name: contributionDays
fields.description: The days of contributions in this week.

fields.name: firstDay
fields.description: The date of the earliest square in this week.

types.name: ContributionLevel
types.description: Varying levels of contributions from none to many.

types.name: ContributionsCollection
types.description: A contributions collection aggregates contributions such as opened issues and commits created by a user.

fields.name: commitContributionsByRepository
fields.description: Commit contributions made by the user, grouped by repository.

fields.name: contributionCalendar
fields.description: A calendar of this user's contributions on GitHub.

fields.name: contributionYears
fields.description: The years the user has been making contributions with the most recent year first.

fields.name: doesEndInCurrentMonth
fields.description: Determine if this collection's time span ends in the current month.

fields.name: earliestRestrictedContributionDate
fields.description: The date of the first restricted contribution the user made in this time period. Can only be non-null when the user has enabled private contribution counts.

fields.name: endedAt
fields.description: The ending date and time of this collection.

fields.name: firstIssueContribution
fields.description: The first issue the user opened on GitHub. This will be null if that issue was opened outside the collection's time range and ignoreTimeRange is false. If the issue is not visible but the user has opted to show private contributions, a RestrictedContribution will be returned.

fields.name: firstPullRequestContribution
fields.description: The first pull request the user opened on GitHub. This will be null if that pull request was opened outside the collection's time range and ignoreTimeRange is not true. If the pull request is not visible but the user has opted to show private contributions, a RestrictedContribution will be returned.

fields.name: firstRepositoryContribution
fields.description: The first repository the user created on GitHub. This will be null if that first repository was created outside the collection's time range and ignoreTimeRange is false. If the repository is not visible, then a RestrictedContribution is returned.

fields.name: hasActivityInThePast
fields.description: Does the user have any more activity in the timeline that occurred prior to the collection's time range?

fields.name: hasAnyContributions
fields.description: Determine if there are any contributions in this collection.

fields.name: hasAnyRestrictedContributions
fields.description: Determine if the user made any contributions in this time frame whose details are not visible because they were made in a private repository. Can only be true if the user enabled private contribution counts.

fields.name: isSingleDay
fields.description: Whether or not the collector's time span is all within the same day.

fields.name: issueContributions
fields.description: A list of issues the user opened.

fields.name: issueContributionsByRepository
fields.description: Issue contributions made by the user, grouped by repository.

fields.name: joinedGitHubContribution
fields.description: When the user signed up for GitHub. This will be null if that sign up date falls outside the collection's time range and ignoreTimeRange is false.

fields.name: latestRestrictedContributionDate
fields.description: The date of the most recent restricted contribution the user made in this time period. Can only be non-null when the user has enabled private contribution counts.

fields.name: mostRecentCollectionWithActivity
fields.description:
When this collection's time range does not include any activity from the user, use this
to get a different collection from an earlier time range that does have activity.

fields.name: mostRecentCollectionWithoutActivity
fields.description:
Returns a different contributions collection from an earlier time range than this one
that does not have any contributions.

fields.name: popularIssueContribution
fields.description:
The issue the user opened on GitHub that received the most comments in the specified
time frame.

fields.name: popularPullRequestContribution
fields.description:
The pull request the user opened on GitHub that received the most comments in the
specified time frame.

fields.name: pullRequestContributions
fields.description: Pull request contributions made by the user.

fields.name: pullRequestContributionsByRepository
fields.description: Pull request contributions made by the user, grouped by repository.

fields.name: pullRequestReviewContributions
fields.description:
Pull request review contributions made by the user. Returns the most recently
submitted review for each PR reviewed by the user.

fields.name: pullRequestReviewContributionsByRepository
fields.description: Pull request review contributions made by the user, grouped by repository.

fields.name: repositoryContributions
fields.description: A list of repositories owned by the user that the user created in this time range.

fields.name: restrictedContributionsCount
fields.description: A count of contributions made by the user that the viewer cannot access. Only non-zero when the user has chosen to share their private contribution counts.

fields.name: startedAt
fields.description: The beginning date and time of this collection.

fields.name: totalCommitContributions
fields.description: How many commits were made by the user in this time span.

fields.name: totalIssueContributions
fields.description: How many issues the user opened.

fields.name: totalPullRequestContributions
fields.description: How many pull requests the user opened.

fields.name: totalPullRequestReviewContributions
fields.description: How many pull request reviews the user left.

fields.name: totalRepositoriesWithContributedCommits
fields.description: How many different repositories the user committed to.

fields.name: totalRepositoriesWithContributedIssues
fields.description: How many different repositories the user opened issues in.

fields.name: totalRepositoriesWithContributedPullRequestReviews
fields.description: How many different repositories the user left pull request reviews in.

fields.name: totalRepositoriesWithContributedPullRequests
fields.description: How many different repositories the user opened pull requests in.

fields.name: totalRepositoryContributions
fields.description: How many repositories the user created.

fields.name: user
fields.description: The user who made the contributions in this collection.

fields.name: createCommitOnBranch
fields.description:
Appends a commit to the given branch as the authenticated user.

This mutation creates a commit whose parent is the HEAD of the provided
branch and also updates that branch to point to the new commit.
It can be thought of as similar to `git commit`.

### Locating a Branch

Commits are appended to a `branch` of type `Ref`.
This must refer to a git branch (i.e.  the fully qualified path must
begin with `refs/heads/`, although including this prefix is optional.

Callers may specify the `branch` to commit to either by its global node
ID or by passing both of `repositoryNameWithOwner` and `refName`.  For
more details see the documentation for `CommittableBranch`.

### Describing Changes

`fileChanges` are specified as a `FilesChanges` object describing
`FileAdditions` and `FileDeletions`.

Please see the documentation for `FileChanges` for more information on
how to use this argument to describe any set of file changes.

### Authorship

Similar to the web commit interface, this mutation does not support
specifying the author or committer of the commit and will not add
support for this in the future.

A commit created by a successful execution of this mutation will be
authored by the owner of the credential which authenticates the API
request.  The committer will be identical to that of commits authored
using the web interface.

If you need full control over author and committer information, please
use the Git Database REST API instead.

### Commit Signing

Commits made using this mutation are automatically signed by GitHub if
supported and will be marked as verified in the user interface.

fields.name: updateRef

fields.name: updateRefs
fields.description:
Creates, updates and/or deletes multiple refs in a repository.

This mutation takes a list of `RefUpdate`s and performs these updates
on the repository. All updates are performed atomically, meaning that
if one of them is rejected, no other ref will be modified.

`RefUpdate.beforeOid` specifies that the given reference needs to point
to the given value before performing any updates. A value of
`0000000000000000000000000000000000000000` can be used to verify that
the references should not exist.

`RefUpdate.afterOid` specifies the value that the given reference
will point to after performing all updates. A value of
`0000000000000000000000000000000000000000` can be used to delete a
reference.

If `RefUpdate.force` is set to `true`, a non-fast-forward updates
for the given reference will be allowed.

fields.name: vulnerableVersionRange
fields.description:
A string that describes the vulnerable package versions.
This string follows a basic syntax with a few forms.
+ `= 0.2.0` denotes a single vulnerable version.
+ `<= 1.0.8` denotes a version range up to and including the specified version
+ `< 0.1.11` denotes a version range up to, but excluding, the specified version
+ `>= 4.3.0, < 4.3.5` denotes a version range with a known minimum and maximum version.
+ `>= 0.0.1` denotes a version range with a known minimum, but no known maximum

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name and description, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.
